{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568727"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:21:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:21:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21305"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21305"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.22,0.21,0.36,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115152"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14178"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97160"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"12894"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115152"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review prior to a planned dental extraction. He has a history of prosthetic aortic valve replacement two years ago. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He reports an allergy to penicillins, with urticaria and facial swelling. His dentist has requested antibiotic prophylaxis prior to the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Oral examination reveals poor dentition with evidence of dental caries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antibiotic for endocarditis prophylaxis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flucloxacillin","Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole","Amoxicillin","Clindamycin","Doxycycline"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPeople with prosthetic heart valves are at increased risk of infective endocarditis following dental procedures that involve manipulation of the gingival tissue. Prophylactic antibiotics are recommended for these individuals to reduce the risk of this potentially life-threatening infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E or azithromycin is now the recommended alternative for endocarditis prophylaxis in people with a history of severe penicillin hypersensitivity. It provides adequate coverage against oral streptococci, the most common causative organisms in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line agent for endocarditis prophylaxis in people without a penicillin allergy. However, this patient has a documented immediate hypersensitivity reaction, so amoxicillin is contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E was previously recommended as an alternative for patients with penicillin allergy, but is no longer recommended for endocarditis prophylaxis for dental procedures due to the greater risk of severe adverse reactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for endocarditis prophylaxis as it does not provide adequate coverage against oral streptococci, which are the primary pathogens of concern in dental procedure-related endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for endocarditis prophylaxis as it does not provide adequate coverage against oral streptococci.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndocarditis prophylaxis is recommended only for patients at increased risk of developing infective endocarditis who have the highest risk of adverse outcomes. These include patients with:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eprosthetic cardiac valves (including transcatheter-implanted prostheses or homografts)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eprosthetic material used for cardiac valve repair (such as annuloplasty rings and chords), previous infective endocarditis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ecertain types of congenital heart disease (unrepaired cyanotic defects, including palliative shunts and conduits, or repaired defects with residual defects at or adjacent to the site of a prosthetic patch or device, which inhibit endothelialisation)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Erheumatic heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["People with prosthetic heart valves are at increased risk of infective endocarditis and require antibiotic prophylaxis for certain dental procedures.","Doxycycline or azithromycin is now the recommended alternative for endocarditis prophylaxis in people with severe penicillin allergy."],"references":["Antibiotic prophylaxis for dental procedures. Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97160"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21305"}},